Red Cloud Wind LLC Market-Based Rate Tariff
Seller Market-Based Rate Tariff 1. Availability: Seller makes electric energy and capacity available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below. Seller also makes available to any purchaser the ancillary services listed in this Paragraph 1: California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (CAISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30- minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30- minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (PJM) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. Third Party Ancillary Services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability: This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale sales of electric energy and capacity by Seller at market-based rates. 3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 CFR ? 35.36(a), in the Southwest region, and a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 CFR ? 35.36(a), in the Northeast, Northwest, Central, Southwest Power Pool and Southeast regions. 6. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; Part 41, Part 101, and Part 141, except sections 141.14 and 141.15; and with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licenses is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects; and received blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumptions of liabilities. Tecolote Wind LLC, et al., Docket No. ER21-___-000 (2021) (unpublished letter order).

CO-TENANCY, COMMON FACILITIES AND EASEMENT AGREEMENT THIS CO-TENANCY, COMMON FACILITIES AND EASEMENT AGREEMENT (as amended, amended and restated, supplemented or otherwise modified from time to time, this "Agreement"), dated as of December 31, 2020 (the "Effective Date"), is made and entered into by and among Tecolote Wind LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Tecolote"), Red Cloud Wind LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Red Cloud"), Duran Mesa LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Duran Mesa"), and Clines Corners Wind Farm LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Clines Corners Wind"). The Parties agree as set forth below, with the recitals constituting a material and integral part of this Agreement and the Parties' agreements. Capitalized terms used herein and not otherwise defined shall have the meaning assigned thereto in Exhibit D. Recitals A. Each Party has developed, is in the process of developing or contemplates developing its respective Project, and, in furtherance thereof, the Parties wish to set forth certain of their rights and responsibilities in respect of the development and operation of the Wind Farm Complex and the Common Facilities. B. As of the Effective Date, the Parties own or otherwise hold the Common Facilities as tenants in common. C. The Parties wish to undertake the joint development, construction, ownership, operation and maintenance of the Common Facilities Improvements on the Common Facilities Project Lands and agree that, during and following completion of the construction of the Common Facilities Improvements, each of the Parties will own an undivided ownership interest in the Common Facilities Improvements in a proportion equal to its Project Percentage Interest. D. The Parties intend to utilize the Common Facilities in connection with the Projects. Each Party owns its respective Project, and as a party to this Agreement is (i) entitled to the rights and obligations under this Agreement, based on its respective Project Percentage Interest, in the Common Facilities Improvements and to certain easement and access rights across certain lands and in certain facilities held by the other Parties, as more particularly described herein and (ii) required, as necessary, to grant easements and other access rights across certain of its Project Lands, and to grant an undivided ownership in any additional facilities located on its Project Lands which are necessary and intended for the common ownership by or on behalf of all Projects or more than one Project. E. The Parties have (i) each entered into an O&M Agreement with Pattern Operators LP, a Delaware limited partnership, for the operation and management of such Party's Project, (ii) designated Pattern Operators LP as the Operator responsible for operations and maintenance of the Common Facilities (in such capacity, the "Common Facilities Manager") pursuant to that certain Common Facilities Operation and Maintenance Agreement dated as of the Effective Date (the "Common Facilities O&M Agreement") and (iii) agreed to share the cost of such operations and maintenance of the Common Facilities through their respective payment of fees to the Common Facilities Manager. F. The Parties intend to seek mutual economic benefits by jointly bearing the cost of certain Shared Expenses. G. To govern their respective rights and obligations with respect to the Common Facilities, easements or other land rights, including those granted pursuant to, and subject to the terms of, the Common Facilities Land Rights Agreements, and the Shared Expenses, the Parties are entering into this Agreement, which shall be the Parties' expression of their intention to establish and impose mutually beneficial limitations, restrictions, covenants and conditions to provide for the proper and orderly ownership, operation and management of their interests in their respective Projects. AGREEMENT NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing and of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt of which is hereby acknowledged, each of the Parties hereby agrees as follows: 1. DECLARATION OF INTENTION . The Parties hereby declare that their relationship in and to the Common Facilities will be that of tenants in common, expressly subject, however, to the terms, conditions, limitations and requirements set forth in this Agreement. Nothing contained in this Agreement shall be deemed to constitute the Parties as partners or joint venturers. 2. COMMON FACILITIES, SHARED EXPENSES, ETC. 2.1 Development and Ownership of the Common Facilities Improvements; Use of Red Cloud Gen-Tie; Interconnection Limit . (a) Each Party shall coordinate and cooperate in good faith with each other Party on all matters relating to the Common Facilities, in order to undertake and facilitate the joint development, construction, ownership, operation and maintenance of the Common Facilities Improvements on the Common Facilities Project Lands. The Parties agree that all costs associated with the design, engineering and construction of the Common Facilities Improvements shall be borne by the Parties in accordance with their Project Percentage Interest and upon payment of any such costs by one Party pursuant to the applicable construction agreement(s), the other applicable Parties shall reimburse such Party for their respective Project Percentage Interest of such costs. The Parties agree that all costs associated with the operation and maintenance of the Common Facilities will be shared by the Parties as set forth herein. (b) The Parties agree that, during and upon completion of the construction of the Common Facilities Improvements, each of the Parties will own an undivided ownership interest in the Common Facilities Improvements in a proportion equal to its Project Percentage Interest. On or prior to the Commencement Date (as defined in the Common Facilities O&M Agreement), each Party shall execute and deliver to the other Parties a Bill of Sale in the form attached hereto as Exhibit F conveying the Common Facilities Improvements owned by such Party in accordance with the foregoing. At the time after the Commencement Date (as defined in the Common Facilities O&M Agreement), to the extent any of the Common Facilities Improvements are fixtures and deemed to be real property, the Parties shall evidence of record each Party's ownership interest in such Common Facilities Improvements that constitutes fixtures by executing and recording, in the official real property records of the county clerk's office of each county in which any such Common Facilities Improvements are located, any and all documentation necessary to establish the Parties' respective legal title in and to such Common Facilities Improvements. Unless otherwise agreed upon by the Parties, each portion of the Common Facilities Improvements shall be in the name of all Parties, specifying, if applicable, that each Party's ownership interest is held in a proportion equal to its Project Percentage Interest (provided that the foregoing shall exclude any Party whose ownership interest in any such portion of the Common Facilities Improvements is equal to zero percent (0%)). (c) Consistent with its Interconnection Agreement, each Party shall be entitled to use the Red Cloud Gen-Tie to transmit electricity from the Project of such Party to the Point of Interconnection, in an amount up to its Project Percentage Interest multiplied by the total capacity of the Red Cloud Gen-Tie. Each Party covenants not at any time to interconnect with the Red Cloud Gen-Tie electric generation facilities with an aggregate capacity that exceeds such Party's Project Percentage Interest multiplied by the total capacity of the Red Cloud Gen-Tie. (d) Each Party covenants not at any time to inject energy at the Point of Interconnection in an aggregate amount that exceeds the lesser of (i) the maximum capacity such Party is permitted to interconnect pursuant to its Interconnection Agreement and (ii) if the Common Facilities Manager has directed such Party that it may not inject more energy than a specified amount of energy pursuant to Section 2.1(d)(iv) of the Common Facilities O&M Agreement, then such specified amount. (e) The Parties acknowledge and agree that, pursuant to the Common Facilities O&M Agreement, (i) the Common Facilities Manager will be the single point of contact with the Transmission Provider and has agreed to be responsible for coordinating operations of voltage control among the Projects pursuant to each Party's respective interconnection agreements (provided, however, that such agreement shall not affect each Party's obligation to cooperate to manage voltage and respond to the Transmission Providers' operating instructions as required under its respective Interconnection Agreements) and (ii) the Common Facilities Manager will notify the Transmission Provider of any request from a Person that is not a Party to this Agreement, to interconnect generation facilities to the Common Facilities. 2.2 Shared Expenses . (a) Each Party hereby confirms its obligation to share in the periodic payment of Shared Expenses, and agrees, severally but not jointly, to pay its Project Percentage Interest of the Shared Expenses as and when due and payable. (b) Contemporaneously with the execution of this Agreement, the Parties shall execute and deliver counterparts to the Common Facilities O&M Agreement. Except as expressly provided to the contrary in this Agreement, the Common Facilities Manager shall, on behalf of the Parties, pay all Shared Expenses, and each Party shall reimburse the Common Facilities Manager its respective Project Percentage Interest of such Shared Expenses, in each case in accordance with this Agreement, the Common Facilities O&M Agreement, and each Party's Interconnection Agreement. Each Party shall timely and fully discharge its obligations under the Common Facilities O&M Agreement. (c) As it becomes practicable and desirable, the Parties from time to time may designate additional expenses as Shared Expenses to be administered by the Common Facilities Manager in accordance with this Section 2.2. Each further designation of Shared Expenses may be proposed by any Party, but shall only be approved by an amendment to this Agreement in accordance with Section 9.3. If any Party defaults in the payment of a Shared Expense following receipt of an invoice from the Common Facilities Manager, the other Party or Parties may, after providing the defaulting Party with notice in accordance with Section 9.1, make such payment on behalf of the defaulting Party and the defaulting Party shall promptly reimburse the paying Party for all amounts paid by such paying Party on the defaulting Party's behalf, including interest on such amounts at the Default Rate. (d) The Parties shall notify the Common Facilities Manager of any amendment to the definition of Project Percentage Interest or any other change in the allocation of Shared Expenses in writing at least forty-five (45) days prior to the effective date thereof. The Parties acknowledge that, (i) pursuant to the Common Facilities O&M Agreement, the Common Facilities Manager is obligated to provide the Transmission Provider with notice of any such amendment or other change in writing at least thirty (30) days prior to the effective date thereof, and (ii) each Party will be liable to Transmission Provider for its share of such costs as allocated in accordance with the methodology that Transmission Provider has received notice of. 2.3 Common Facilities Land Rights Agreement . (a) Prior to the Effective Date, (i) each of Red Cloud and Duran Mesa has executed and delivered to Tecolote a Common Facilities Land Rights Agreement in the form attached hereto as Exhibit B-1-A granting Tecolote non-exclusive rights to the Common Facilities Project Lands held by such Party and (ii) Red Cloud and Duran Mesa have each executed and delivered to the other counterparts to a Common Facilities Land Rights Agreement in the form attached hereto as Exhibit B-1-B, pursuant to which Red Cloud has granted to Duran Mesa, and Duran Mesa has granted to Red Cloud, non-exclusive rights to the Common Facilities Project Lands held by such Party. Any Party may obtain direct easements from landowners for its use for the purposes for which a Common Facilities Land Rights Agreement is granted and such Party shall have the right to terminate such Common Facilities Land Rights Agreement in whole or in part after obtaining such direct easement. If a Party attempts to obtain such a direct easement, any Party which then holds an existing leasehold or easement interest in the applicable real property (which is the subject of the direct easement) agrees to waive such Party's right to exclusivity granted to such Party by the applicable landowner, in order to permit such landowner to grant such a direct easement as contemplated in this Section 2.3. (b) Upon request by a Party, each of Red Cloud and Duran Mesa agrees to provide a confirmatory copy of any Common Facilities Land Rights Agreement, together with such additional detailed descriptions and other identifying information of any part of the Common Facilities Project Lands as (and in such form as) a Party may reasonably request, to confirm the vesting of or more accurately describe the real property subject to the sublease and/or subeasement rights to the applicable Common Facilities Project Lands. 2.4 Wind and Other Data . Each Party agrees to share with the other Parties its current and historical wind, avian, wildlife, and meteorological data collected from anemometers, radar and other equipment from locations on its Project Lands and any other material information of such type obtained from such Party's ordinary course use of its Project Lands. The sharing Party makes no representation or warranty, express or implied, and shall have no liability with respect to the information so provided, whether for completeness, accuracy or otherwise. The receiving Party shall maintain the confidentiality of the information received in accordance with the requirements of this Agreement. 2.5 Consent to Relocate Turbine . Without the written consent of the other Parties, no Party may move any of its respective wind turbines from the location of such wind turbines as of the date of the completion of the construction of such Party's Project. 2.6 Project Owner Rights . (a) Each Party agrees that subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the owner of any Project shall have the right and obligation to share, in accordance with its Project Percentage Interest, in the benefits, costs and liabilities of the Common Facilities. (b) Upon request of a Party, the other Parties shall, at the requesting Party's sole expense, take such commercially reasonable actions as the requesting Party shall reasonably request to confirm that such Party possesses sufficient real property rights in respect to the Project Lands on which such Party's Project is located in order to develop or sell such Party's Project or any interest therein in an orderly, financeable and saleable manner; such actions to include the granting of easements, sub-easements, subleases or other real property rights to the requesting Party in respect to the lands in which any such other Party already owns or holds an interest for, among other things, access for development, construction, operation, maintenance and repair of communications systems, substations, electrical collection systems and transmission systems, and if requested the Parties will cooperate and assist the requesting Party (at the requesting Party's sole cost) in obtaining such real property rights from the owners of such lands. Notwithstanding the foregoing, to the extent any Party has a different direct or indirect equity holder from any other Party, such other Parties will not be required to take any such action if such action impairs in any material respect the construction, operation, maintenance or repair of such Party's Project. (c) Each Party acknowledges and agrees that the interconnection of, operation of and/or any changes in such Party's Project (an "Impacting Owner") that require or result in scheduled and/or unscheduled outages and/or curtailment of some or all of the energy production from any of the other Parties' respective Project (a "Curtailment") may result in (i) claims from third parties against any of the Parties not causing the Curtailment (each, an "Affected Owner"), and (ii) lost revenues of such Affected Owner (including the cash value of any lost federal production tax credits, grossed up based on the actual federal income tax rate applicable to such Affected Owner, penalties imposed on such Affected Owner or damages payable by such Affected Owner to a power purchaser, energy hedge provider or transmission service provider for such Affected Owner's Project) (together with related costs and/or expenses, collectively, "Affected Owner Curtailment Losses"); provided that in no event shall curtailment of a Project arising as a result of or in connection with congestion or otherwise resulting from the ordinary course of operation of the Projects constitute a "Curtailment" pursuant to this Section 2.6(c). All Affected Owner Curtailment Losses shall be the sole responsibility of the Impacting Owner. If an Impacting Owner's Curtailment is scheduled (a "Scheduled Curtailment"), the Parties shall establish a protocol to reasonably minimize disruptions to any Affected Owner's Project during the period of the Scheduled Curtailment. Prior to beginning any activities related to a Scheduled Curtailment, each Affected Owner shall estimate in good faith the anticipated Affected Owner Curtailment Losses and deliver such estimate to the Impacting Owner. Upon the conclusion of any Curtailment, whether planned or unplanned, each Affected Owner shall determine its actual Affected Owner Curtailment Losses and deliver reasonable backup documentation supporting the calculation thereof to the Impacting Owner. Any dispute regarding the calculation of Affected Owner Curtailment Losses shall be determined by the Independent Engineer. The Impacting Owner shall promptly pay all undisputed Affected Owner Curtailment Losses to the applicable Affected Owner and, if applicable, the costs of engaging the Independent Engineer for the services required under this Section 2.6(c) following receipt of the calculation of the Affected Owner Curtailment Losses from such Affected Owner. Each Affected Owner shall have all other rights and remedies as may be provided in this Agreement otherwise available at law or in equity resulting from an Impacting Owner's failure to pay to such Affected Owner all Affected Owner Curtailment Losses. (d) Unless specifically provided in this Agreement, each Party shall have the right to vote or give its approval, on any matter requiring or needing a vote or approval of the Parties. Unless otherwise specified herein, a vote of a Majority of the Parties shall be required for any approval to be provided by the Parties hereunder. 3. TERM . The term of this Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date, and, unless sooner terminated by mutual agreement of the Parties or the consolidation of ownership of the Common Facilities Improvements in a single Party, shall continue as to each Party for the commercial life of its Project, not to exceed fifty (50) years from the Effective Date. 4. CONDITION OF PROPERTY AND COMPLIANCE WITH LAWS . Each Party accepts the Common Facilities in their condition existing as of the Effective Date on an "As-Is" basis and subject to all Laws and, except as otherwise provided in Section 5.4, all covenants, conditions, reservations, restrictions, easements, liens, encumbrances and other matters affecting the Common Facilities as of the Effective Date. Each Party acknowledges that no other Party nor any of their respective representatives or agents has made any representation or warranty as to the suitability of the Common Facilities or any portion thereof for the conduct of the operations of any other Party, any of the Projects or for any other purpose. Prior to the energization of the Common Facilities, (a) Red Cloud shall file this Agreement with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act as a FERC-filed rate schedule, (b) each of the other Parties shall file a certificate of concurrence as described in FERC's rules and regulations with FERC assenting and concurring in the filing of this Agreement as a rate schedule of the Party filing the Certificate of Compliance and (c) FERC shall have accepted all such filings. 5. INDEMNITY, USE AND COMPLIANCE. 5.1 Indemnity . Each Party (an "Indemnifying Party") shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Parties and their respective Indemnitees (each, an "Indemnified Party") from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including reasonable attorneys' and consultants' fees, which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Party or asserted against such Indemnified Party by any third Person in connection with (a) any negligent or willful acts, bad faith or reckless misconduct or omissions (where such Indemnifying Party (or any of its directors, officers, partners, members, Affiliates, employees, agents, successors and assigns) has a legal or contractual duty to act) of or on behalf of the Indemnifying Party or its directors, officers, partners, members, Affiliates, employees, agents, successors and assigns, on or with respect to its Project Controlled Assets, and (b) the breach of the Indemnifying Party's obligations under this Agreement. Notwithstanding anything contained in this Agreement to the contrary, each Party's obligations under this Section 5.1 shall survive the expiration of the term of this Agreement or earlier termination of this Agreement; provided, however that any such obligation shall survive such expiration or earlier termination only to the extent that the event giving rise to a claim for indemnification under this Section 5.1 shall have arisen prior to such expiration or earlier termination. 5.2 Environmental Compliance . Without limiting the scope of each Party's obligations under Section 5.1, each Party shall, with respect to its Project and Project Lands (other than any portion of the Project Lands that constitutes Common Facilities), be responsible for all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any governmental authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters (for the avoidance of doubt, "environmental" matters include, but are not limited to, the protection of natural resources and wildlife) or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to such Party's development, construction, use, operation or ownership of its Project or Project Lands, except to the extent that such investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action are required in response to the actions, negligence, misconduct or negligent omissions of another Party in which case such other Party shall be responsible for all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action to the extent arising from its negligence, misconduct or negligent omissions. Each Party shall have the right (but not the obligation, unless otherwise required above) to participate in the management and control of all investigations and any environmental cleanup, remediation or related activities relating to its Project or Project Lands. With respect to the Common Facilities, the Common Facilities Manager shall oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any governmental authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the Parties' use, operation or ownership, as applicable, of the Common Facilities, and subject to Section 5.1 (as between the Parties), each Party shall be responsible, in proportion to its Project Percentage Interest, determined as of the date of the event resulting in any such investigation, environmental cleanup, corrective action or response or remedial action, for all liabilities related to such investigations, studies, clean-up, corrective action or response or remedial action, except to the extent that such investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action are required in response to the actions, negligence, misconduct or negligent omissions of a Party, in which case such Party shall be responsible for the costs and expenses all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action to the extent arising from its actions, negligence, misconduct or negligent omissions. Each Party covenants and agrees to promptly provide a copy to each other Party of any written correspondence between it and any governmental authority with respect to environmental matters relating to the Common Facilities or its Project Controlled Assets to the extent that it could reasonably be expected to materially and adversely affect the Common Facilities or another Party's Project Controlled Assets. 5.3 No Waste or Nuisance; Maintenance; No Interference . No Party shall use or permit the use of the Common Facilities in any manner that would create waste or cause a nuisance, or that would increase the rate, or jeopardize the issuance or maintenance, of any insurance policy relating to the Common Facilities and/or any Project Lands, nor otherwise conduct or cause to be conducted operations on its Project Lands which would have similar effects on, or otherwise damage or interfere with, the Common Facilities located on its Project Lands. The Parties shall at all times while conducting their respective operations and activities on the Wind Farm Complex make reasonable efforts to minimize the impact of such operations and activities upon any other Party's use of the Common Facilities. 5.4 Liens . Each Party shall have the right to grant liens to Lenders providing financing for the construction or operation of its Project or otherwise in such Party's undivided interests in the Common Facilities and its interests under and pursuant to the applicable Common Facilities Land Rights Agreement as provided in Section 7 of this Agreement; provided, however, that (a) no Party shall cause or permit any lien or encumbrance to be levied against or attached to any other Party's interests in the Common Facilities and (b) all Transfers of undivided interests in the Common Facilities shall be free of any lien or encumbrance. 5.5 Taxes . Each Party shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Project, Project Lands (to the extent the applicable Party is responsible for the payment of such taxes), or the facilities and fixtures located thereon. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment. 5.6 Insurance . Each Party shall, at its sole cost and expense, procure and maintain during the term of this Agreement, and provide the other Parties with acceptable evidence (in form and substance reasonably satisfactory to the other Parties) of the existence of, the types and amounts of insurance listed in Schedule 5.6. Each Party shall require each of their insurers to waive any and all rights of subrogation, recovery or counter claim in favor each other Party. The insurance required under this Section 5.6 and in Schedule 5.6 may be provided under a combined insurance program naming all Parties as insureds with shared policy limits, which shall operate in the same manner as if there were separate policies covering each insured independently of the other but only to the extent of the required insurance limits herein and solely regarding claims for which each Party has in this Agreement agreed to provide defense and indemnity. 5.7 Certain Agreements to Indemnify, Hold Harmless, Insure or Defend: Limitations. The intent of the Parties to this Agreement is to have their indemnity and other agreements, if and to the extent they are subject to New Mexico's indemnity-limiting statutes, NMSA 1978, ? 56-7-1 (2005) and NMSA 1978 ? 56-7-2 (2003), enforced pursuant to their respective terms and limited only to the extent necessary to conform with and survive such indemnity-limiting statutes (i) as in effect at the time of the parties' entry into this Agreement, and (ii) as subsequently amended if it is determined by a court or arbitrator of competent jurisdiction that one or both such statutes is/are applicable as subsequently amended. Accordingly, the Parties agree that this Section 5.7 will only apply to the extent necessary to reform the indemnity and other agreements of the parties that are subject to New Mexico's indemnity-limiting statutes so that the same will be enforceable pursuant to their respective terms and comply with and not be void as a result of the application of NMSA 1978, ? 56-7-1 (2005) or NMSA 1978 ? 56-7-2 (2003). The Parties reaffirm their intent that this Agreement be governed by, and construed in accordance with, the governing law chosen in Section 9.9. To the extent, if at all, that any provision contained in this Agreement, including any exhibits or schedules hereto, or other related documents requiring one Party to indemnify, hold harmless, insure, or defend another Party (including such other Party's employees or agents) is found by a court or arbitrator of competent jurisdiction, or by all of the Parties, to be within the scope of NMSA 1978, ? 56-7-1 (2005) or in any way subject to, or conditioned upon consistency with, the provisions of NMSA 1978, ? 56-7-1 (2005) for its enforceability, then regardless of whether such provision makes reference to this or any other limitation provision, to the maximum extent allowed under applicable law: (A) such provision shall not, and is not intended to, extend to liability, claims, damages, losses or expenses, including attorney fees, arising out of bodily injury to persons or damage to property caused by or resulting from, in whole or in part, the negligence, act or omission of the indemnitee or additional insured, as the case may be, its officers, employees or agents, to the extent of the indemnitee's or additional insured's own negligence, act or omission, so long as this qualification is consistent with applicable New Mexico law; (B) such provision shall be enforced only to the extent that the liability, damages, losses or costs are caused by, or arise out of, the acts or omissions of the indemnitor or its officers, employees or agents; and (C) such provision shall be further or otherwise modified, if required, by, or to be consistent with (x) the terms of NMSA 1978, ? 56-7-1 (2005) as in effect at the time of the parties' entry into this Agreement, (y) the provisions of NMSA 1978, ? 56-7-1 (2005) as subsequently amended if it is determined by a court or arbitrator of competent jurisdiction that such statute is applicable as amended, and (z) New Mexico appellate decisions interpreting NMSA 1978, ? 56-7-1 (2005), including as amended if it is determined by a court or arbitrator of competent jurisdiction that such statute is applicable as amended. Further, with respect to (1) any agreement, covenant, or promise to indemnify another party contained in this Agreement, any exhibits or schedules to this Agreement or other related document (herein referred to as an "Indemnification Covenant" for purposes of the remainder of this Section 5.7, and (2) any provision in an insurance contract indemnity agreement naming a person as an additional insured, or in an insurance contract or other contract requiring a waiver of rights of subrogation or otherwise having the effect of imposing a duty of indemnification on a primary insured party, contained in or required by this Agreement, including any exhibits or schedules, or any related document (hereinafter referred to as an "Insurance Provision" for purposes of the remainder of this Section 5.7, the Parties agree as set out in the balance of this paragraph. Notwithstanding any other term or condition of this Agreement or any Indemnification Covenant or any Insurance Provision, to the extent, if at all, that the Agreement or any such Indemnification Covenant or any Insurance Provision is found by a court or arbitrator of competent jurisdiction, or by all of the Parties, to be within the scope of NMSA 1978, ? OPERATION AND MANAGEMENT . Each Party is required to operate and maintain its Project and Project Lands (other than any portion of such Project Lands that constitutes Common Facilities Project Lands, which shall be operated and maintained by the Common Facilities Manager), and to utilize the Common Facilities, acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (a) in a safe manner, (b) in accordance with good operating practice, (c) in compliance with all Laws and (d) without causing a material adverse effect on any other Party. The Parties acknowledge that, pursuant to the Common Facilities O&M Agreement, the Common Facilities Manager will be responsible for responding to any directive from the Transmission Provider to interrupt service. To the extent required for enforcement, each Party to which any warranty was issued with respect to any of the Common Facilities shall, at the request and expense of any other Party, pursue any claims in respect of such warranty for the benefit of each of the Parties. All performance by the Common Facilities Manager in relation to the Common Facilities shall constitute the performance by the applicable Party of its obligations under this Agreement relating thereto; provided, however, that upon the default of the Common Facilities Manager of any such obligation, the applicable Party shall remain obligated to perform such obligation. Payment for all expenses relating to Common Facilities that are not covered by the Common Facilities O&M Agreement shall be made by the responsible Party before any penalty for non-payment shall be assessed and in a timely enough manner so that neither the Common Facilities nor the Common Facilities Land Rights Agreements will be jeopardized or made subject to any lien or encumbrance. Each Party shall bear the risk of damage, loss, condemnation, or taking to or of its Project and Project Lands (other than any portion of such Project Lands that constitutes Common Facilities). 7. (a) No Party may Transfer its interest in this Agreement without the prior written consent of the other Parties; provided, however, that any Party (a "Transferring Party") shall be permitted, without obtaining the consent of the other Parties, to Transfer all or part of its interest in this Agreement in connection with the Transfer of all or part of its Project Controlled Assets and its interests in the Common Facilities, so long as, as a condition to such Transfer, the transferee shall agree in writing, pursuant to an agreement substantially in the form attached hereto as Exhibit E, to become a Party to this Agreement and to assume for the benefit of the other Parties all prior, existing and future rights, liabilities and obligations of the Transferring Party hereunder with respect to the Project Controlled Assets and interests in the Common Facilities Transferred thereto. In the event a Lender or any party taking a security interest or a collateral assignment of a Party's rights in this Agreement, the Common Facilities, the applicable Common Facilities Land Rights Agreement and/or the Transmission Easements, exercises any rights or remedies of such Lender or other party, the exercise of such rights or remedies shall not constitute a Transfer or otherwise require the consent of any of the Parties; provided that, in no event, shall such Party encumber the interests of any other Party in this Agreement, the Common Facilities, the Common Facilities Land Rights Agreements and/or the Transmission Easements. In addition, in connection with the Financing of each Project, each Party shall upon the reasonable request of another Party, cooperate in the requesting Party's Financing or credit or any refinancing thereof, including by providing customary estoppels and consents in favor of any Lender, including rights of step-in with respect to such requesting Party's obligations under this Agreement and rights to concurrent notice of default or such other matter as may be reasonably requested by the requesting Party or its Lenders, and in the making of any filings reasonably required by such requesting Party for regulatory compliance, which are customary for comparable transactions and consistent with the terms hereof, all solely at the expense of the requesting Party and at no out-of-pocket costs to any other Party. All reasonable expenses, including reasonable attorneys' fees, incurred in connection with a Transfer or proposed assignment of such Party's undivided interests hereunder or the actual or proposed pledge, collateral assignment, encumbrance or grant of a security interest in a Party's undivided interests and its rights under this Agreement to a Lender shall be reimbursed by the Transferring/borrowing Party upon written request therefor by another Party. Any Party requesting reimbursement for its expenses shall provide reasonable supporting documentation for such expenses to the Transferring/borrowing Party together with the request therefor. DEFAULT, REMEDIES AND FORCE MAJEURE. 8.1 Events of Default; Default . If a Party shall fail to perform its obligations hereunder in any material respect, then such failure shall not constitute a default hereunder unless such Party shall have failed to cure such default within five (5) days after receipt of written notice of a payment default, or thirty (30) days after such Party has obtained knowledge or received written notice of any other default, from a non-defaulting Party; provided, however, that if (a) the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations other than a payment default (for which no additional cure is permitted) is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for performance of such obligation(s) and (b) the existence of such breach has not resulted in and would not, after considering the nature of the cure, be reasonably expected to give rise to a circumstance requiring more timely action to prevent any loss of rights or damage or injury to persons or property, or otherwise have a material adverse effect on the Common Facilities, then such non-performing Party shall not be in default if it commences such performance within such thirty (30) day period and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed ninety (90) days, including the initial cure period. (i) A Party's failure to comply with the cure periods set forth above, or (ii) the occurrence of the following events with respect to a Party, including (A) any filing of a petition or action under any bankruptcy law, (B) any affirmative act of insolvency (including the consent to the entry of an order for relief in an involuntary case, consent to the appointment of a receiver, any assignment for the benefit of creditors, or the admission of its inability to pay its debt as they become due), (C) the filing of an involuntary petition under any bankruptcy law that is not dismissed or stayed within sixty (60) days thereafter, or (D) the appointment of a receiver or trustee, which appointment is not dismissed or stayed within sixty (60) days thereafter shall constitute an "Event of Default". 8.2 Remedies . In addition to all other remedies permitted by Law or under this Agreement (all of which shall be cumulative), following an Event of Default: (a) a non-defaulting Party and its Lenders or other interest holders shall be entitled following an Event of Default to perform the obligations of the defaulting Party, and the defaulting Party shall reimburse a performing Party for the expenses that it incurred in rendering the performance, plus interest at the Default Rate, and (b) a non-defaulting Party may require that the Common Facilities Manager disconnect the defaulting Party's Project from the Common Facilities Improvements; provided, that the defaulting Party's Project shall be permitted to reconnect promptly when and if (i) the default is cured, and (ii) any and all damages suffered and incurred by the non-defaulting Parties have been compensated in a manner consistent with this Agreement and the Common Facilities O&M Agreement, with interest paid at the Default Rate; provided further, that no Party shall have the right to disconnect any Project from the Common Facilities Improvements other than in accordance with this Section 8.2(b). (c) The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for a default under this Agreement, and that each Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief including specific performance against another Party to prevent or eliminate such default. 8.3 Force Majeure . If performance of this Agreement or of any obligation hereunder is prevented or substantially restricted or interfered with by reason of an event of Force Majeure, the affected Party shall be excused from such performance to the extent of and for the duration of such Force Majeure event. The affected Party shall use diligent and commercially reasonable efforts to avoid or remove such causes of nonperformance and shall continue performance as soon as such causes are removed. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the affected Party shall not be relieved from its monetary obligations arising pursuant to this Agreement. 9. GENERAL PROVISIONS. 9.1 Notices . If a Party receiving any such confidential information (the "Receiving Party") is required to disclose any such confidential information pursuant to any subpoena or any other equivalent legal process, the Receiving Party shall promptly notify the Party who disclosed such confidential information (the "Disclosing Party") so that the Disclosing Party can seek a protective order from the court having jurisdiction in such matter or otherwise seek to prevent or limit the scope or impose conditions upon such disclosure. Notwithstanding anything contained herein, confidential information shall not include information (x) that was publicly available at the time of the disclosure thereof or (y) that becomes publicly available other than through actions of the Receiving Party or any of its Representatives in violation of this Agreement. 9.12 Dispute Resolution . (a) The Parties will attempt, in good faith, to resolve or cure all disputes and claims before initiating any legal action or attempting to enforce any rights or remedies under this Agreement, at law or in equity (regardless of whether this Section 9.12 is referenced in the provision of this Agreement which is the basis for any such dispute). If any Party believes that a breach or a dispute under this Agreement has arisen, such Party will give written notice thereof to the other Parties, which notice will describe in reasonable detail the basis and specifics of the claimed breach or dispute. Within five (5) days after delivery of such notice, the Parties will meet (in person or via telephone) to discuss and attempt to resolve or cure such dispute or claimed breach. If the Parties are unable to resolve the dispute or claimed breach within fifteen (15) days after delivery of such notice, the matter will be referred to a senior officer of each Party for resolution or cure. If such senior officers are unable to agree on an appropriate cure or resolution within ten (10) days after the matter has been referred to them, the Parties may have recourse to mediation, arbitration, or other alternative dispute resolution device of their mutual selection. If the Parties cannot agree on an alternative dispute resolution device, then any Party may submit the dispute to arbitration pursuant to Section 9.12(c) of this Agreement. (b) Pending final resolution of any dispute, the Parties will continue to fulfill their respective obligations under this Agreement; provided that the applicable Party may withhold any amount which is the subject of dispute from any payment otherwise due under this Agreement during the pendency of any dispute resolution proceeding. Upon resolution of the dispute, any Party found owing an amount will promptly pay to the other Parties any amount determined to be due. (c) Any disputes, controversies or claims arising out of or in connection with this Agreement, including any question regarding its existence, validity or expiration but excluding specific performance or injunctive relief, will be finally and completely resolved without appeal by arbitration under the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association ("AAA Rules") in force at the date of the request for arbitration, which AAA Rules are deemed to be incorporated by reference into this section; provided, however, that in the event of any conflict between such rules and the other provisions of this Agreement, such other provisions of this Agreement will control; and provided, further, that discovery shall be conducted consistent with the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, as determined by the arbitrators. The arbitral tribunal will consist of three arbitrators, each of whom shall be fluent in English. The Party initiating the arbitration shall appoint one arbitrator and the Party or Parties responding to the arbitration notice shall appoint one arbitrator. If any of the Parties fails to appoint an arbitrator within thirty (30) days of receiving notice of an appointment of an arbitrator by the other Party or Parties, such arbitrator shall at the request of any Party be appointed by the President of the American Arbitration Association. The two arbitrators so appointed shall, within thirty (30) days of the date of the appointment of the second arbitrator, appoint a third arbitrator who shall act as the chairman of the tribunal. If the two arbitrators to be appointed fail to agree upon a third arbitrator within thirty (30) days of the appointment of the second arbitrator, then the third arbitrator will be appointed by the President of the American Arbitration Association at the written request of either Party. The arbitration proceedings will take place in New Mexico and the language of such proceedings, including arguments and briefs, will be English. The proceedings will be confidential in all respects. The award of the arbitrators will be by majority vote and will be in writing, will set forth the facts found by the arbitrators to exist, their determination and the basis of their determination. Any award will be made in US dollars. Notwithstanding any provision of this Agreement which may be interpreted to the contrary, the arbitral tribunal will not have the authority to award consequential or punitive damages; provided that any damages or remedies that are expressly set forth in this Agreement (including the cash value of any lost federal production tax credits and any state renewable energy credits) shall not constitute consequential or punitive damages. Each party to a dispute shall bear its own attorneys' fees and expenses. The fees and expenses for the arbitral panel will be borne equally by the Parties involved in the arbitration; provided, however, that the arbitral panel may assess attorney's fees and costs against any party to the dispute. The award of the arbitral tribunal will be final and not subject to appeal and judgment upon the award may be entered in any competent court. 9.13 Memorandum . AGREEMENTS NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing recitals, the mutual covenants and agreements set forth herein and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt of which is hereby acknowledged, Grantor and Grantee hereby agree as follows: SECTION 1 - GRANT OF RIGHTS 1.1 Grant of Land Rights. 1.1.1 Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the Common Facilities Agreement and the Master Land Rights Agreements, Grantor hereby irrevocably and unconditionally grants and conveys to Grantee and its successors and assigns, a nonexclusive easement in, upon, over, across, along, above and under the Property, solely for the purposes more particularly described in Section 1.2 below (the "Land Rights"). 1.1.2 The term of the Land Rights shall expire, as to each portion of the Land Rights, concurrently with the expiration or earlier termination of the Master Land Rights Agreements affecting such portion of the Property. 1.2 Purposes of Land Rights. Subject to and to the extent permitted by this Agreement, the Common Facilities Agreement and the Master Land Rights Agreements, the Land Rights are intended for the following purposes and activities: (a) ingress and egress on, over and across the Property by means of any existing roads and lanes thereon, and by such other roads and lanes as Grantor may construct thereon from time to time for the purpose of accessing the Common Facilities Improvements and (b) constructing the Common Facilities Improvements in, on, over, under, along, across and within a portion of the Property, and operating, maintaining and inspecting the same, and undertaking any other activities, whether accomplished by Grantee or a third party authorized by Grantee, that Grantee determines are necessary, helpful, appropriate or convenient in connection with, incidental to or to accomplish any of the foregoing purposes. 1.3 As-Is Condition. The Land Rights are granted and conveyed to Grantee subject to the present condition of the Property and on an "AS-IS" basis, and Grantee hereby accepts the Land Rights and such property in such condition and on such basis. Grantee acknowledges that neither Grantor nor any of its representatives or agents has made any representation or warranty as to the suitability of the Property or any portion thereof for the conduct of the operations of Grantee or for any other purpose. SECTION 2 - MISCELLANEOUS RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Indemnity. Each Party shall indemnify, defend and hold the other Party and its subgrantees, heirs, successors and assigns harmless from and against any losses, damages, expenses or liabilities resulting from any action of the indemnifying Party and of any Persons (as defined in the Common Facilities Agreement) authorized by, through or under the indemnifying Party on the Property, or any part thereof or any breach of this Agreement. 2.2 Compliance with Law. Each Party shall, at its sole cost and expense, promptly comply with all applicable Laws (as defined in the Common Facilities Agreement) and with all covenants, conditions and restrictions in effect during the term of this Agreement or any part thereof regulating the use of the Property, or any facilities thereon; provided however, that such Party shall have the right to contest by appropriate legal proceedings the validity or applicability of any such Law. 2.3 Liens. Grantor shall pay, when due, all claims for labor or materials furnished to or on behalf of Grantor at or for use on the Property or any part thereof, which claims are or may be secured by any mechanic's or materialmen's lien which affect the use or enjoyment of the Land Rights. Grantee shall pay, when due, all claims for labor or materials furnished to or on behalf of Grantee at or for use on the Property or any part thereof, which claims are or may be secured by any mechanics' or materialmen's lien which affects the use or enjoyment of the Land Rights. 2.4 Right To Assign and Encumber. Grantee shall not, at any time and from time to time, without obtaining the Grantor's consent, (a) transfer, assign, alienate, license or grant all or any portion of its right, title or interest under this Agreement (including by grant of co-tenancy interest or grant of subeasement) to any Person, except as provided in the Common Facilities Agreement, and/or (b) hypothecate, mortgage or pledge all or any portion of its right, title or interest under this Agreement, except as provided in the Common Facilities Agreement. 2.5 Land Rights Subordinate to Master Land Rights Agreements. Notwithstanding anything that may be construed to the contrary herein, this Agreement, and all of the rights of the Parties hereunder, are and shall at all times be subject and subordinate to the Master Land Rights Agreements. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, and notwithstanding anything that may be construed to the contrary in this Agreement: 2.5.1 This Agreement does not and shall not grant to any Party any rights, interests or benefits greater than those provided to or permitted to such Party under the Master Land Rights Agreements; and this Agreement shall in all respects be limited by and taken subject to the terms, conditions and provisions of the Master Land Rights Agreements. Grantor represents and warrants that this Agreement, and the granting of rights, interests and benefits hereunder, do not contravene, conflict with or result in a breach of, or require any consent under any of the Master Land Rights Agreements, other than any consent obtained prior to the date hereof. 2.5.2 The Parties shall not take or fail to take any action, where such action or failure would constitute a default under, or would be inconsistent with the terms and provisions of, any of the Master Land Rights Agreements; and the Parties shall at all times comply with such terms and provisions. 2.5.3 In the event that the terms, conditions or obligations set forth in this Agreement are inconsistent with or contradict the terms, conditions or obligations set forth in the Master Land Rights Agreements, then this Agreement shall control over the Master Land Rights Agreements to the extent that this Agreement conveys fewer rights or benefits, or imposes greater limitations, requirements or obligations on a Party; otherwise the terms, conditions and obligations set forth in the Master Land Rights Agreements shall control. 2.5.4 Grantee hereby assumes and agrees to perform all obligations of Grantor under the Master Land Rights Agreements that are applicable to, and that would bind Grantor in connection with, the operations of Grantee on the Property. 2.6 Rights of the Parties With Respect to the Property. 2.6.1 Grantee shall have the right to undertake only those activities on the Property that are contemplated by the Common Facilities Agreement or this Agreement and that are permitted by the Master Land Rights Agreements. 2.6.2 Grantor hereby reserves the right to undertake any activities on the Property that are permitted by the Master Land Rights Agreements, including the right to (a) build and operate wind power generating facilities and projects, (b) enter into subeasements or subleases, easements, licenses, co-tenancy agreements and other agreements with other Persons and (c) use and cross the Property, and grant or assign such use and crossing rights (or undivided or subordinate interests therein) to other Persons. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, Grantor may grant and convey non-exclusive in gross subeasements over the Property in favor of other Persons for any of the purposes provided in the Master Land Rights Agreements in each case together with (i) all necessary or appropriate rights of way for access, ingress and egress to and from the Property and (ii) the right in the transferee to grant or convey undivided or subordinate interests therein to other Persons. 2.6.3 Grantor reserves the right, in its discretion, to amend, supplement or restate one or more of the Master Land Rights Agreements without the consent of Grantee, and the Parties hereby agree (a) to each such amendment, supplement and restatement and (b) that any such amendment, supplement or restatement shall automatically, and without the need for further documentation, be senior to the Land Rights and the rights of the Parties under this Agreement; provided, however, that no such amendment, supplement or restatement shall have the effect of (i) materially increasing the duties or obligations of the Parties under this Agreement, (ii) materially decreasing the rights or benefits given or afforded to the Parties or the Lenders hereunder or (iii) impairing the security of any Lender's lien. The Parties shall deliver a copy of each such amendment, supplement and restatement to the other and each Lender immediately after the same has been executed. 2.7 Performance of Obligations. Grantor hereby covenants that it will (a) perform its obligations under each of the Master Land Rights Agreements in all material respects and (b) notwithstanding any provision of the Master Land Rights Agreements that would allow Grantor to quitclaim or surrender the same or any portion thereof, either (at Grantor's sole discretion) (i) keep and maintain each of the Master Land Rights Agreements in full force and effect for the full term thereof or (ii) quitclaim the same to Grantee. 2.8 Conduct. Grantee shall (a) conduct or cause to be conducted its operations and activities on the Property and each part thereof in accordance with sound and prudent engineering, operation and maintenance practices and (b) keep its facilities in good condition and repair, in good and efficient working order and in a clean, sanitary and safe condition. Grantee shall not conduct its operations or activities, or use or permit the use of the Property or any part thereof or its facilities in any manner that will create waste or cause a nuisance or that will damage the Property or any part thereof; and each Party shall be liable and responsible to the other Party for any such waste, nuisance or damage. 2.9 Restoration. Within six (6) months after the expiration or earlier termination of this Agreement, if Grantor fails to perform the removal and restoration obligations under the applicable Master Land Rights Agreements, Grantee or its or other designees shall have the right but not the obligation to undertake restoration and removal activities, and shall have a continuing subeasement to enter the Property for such purpose during such six (6)-month period. 2.10 Ownership of Improvements. The Parties acknowledge and agree that (a) Grantor's facilities are and shall be and remain severable and separable from the Property, (b) except as provided herein, Grantee shall have no ownership or other interest in any facilities (other than the Common Facilities Improvements) installed or placed on the Property as separate property by Grantor, and Grantor may remove any or all such facilities owned by Grantor at any time and from time to time, (c) to the extent permitted by Law, Grantee and Grantor each hereby waives any statutory or common law lien that it might otherwise have in or to the facilities or any thereof that are owned separately and not as tenants in common with each other and (d) if such waiver is not enforceable or permitted by Law, then Grantee and Grantor each hereby subordinates each such statutory or common law lien to any Lender's lien from time to time existing against such facilities or any thereof. SECTION 3 - GENERAL PROVISIONS 3.1 Notices. Any notices, statements, demands, correspondence or other communications required or permitted to be given hereunder shall (a) be in writing, (b) be deemed given (i) when personally delivered to the recipient or (ii) two (2) days after delivery to a reputable courier for overnight delivery (provided receipt is obtained and charges are prepaid by the delivering Party) and (c) be addressed to the address of the recipient Party set forth in the preamble hereof, except that each Party hereto may change its address for receipt of notices by sending notice of such change to the other Party in the manner specified in this Section 3.1. 3.2 No Abandonment; Quitclaim. No act or failure to act on the part of the Parties hereto or any other Person shall be deemed to constitute an abandonment of the easement created by this Agreement, except upon recordation by Grantee of a quitclaim deed specifically conveying a subeasement back to Grantor pursuant to this Section 3.2 or a release agreement releasing and extinguishing such subeasement. Grantee may, at any time and from time to time during the term hereof (and shall, upon termination of this Agreement), quitclaim to Grantor the subeasement created by this Agreement and all of the right, title and interest granted to Grantee hereunder, by executing an appropriate quitclaim deed and causing the same to be recorded in the Official Public Records of Torrance County, New Mexico. 3.3 Cooperation. Each Party shall, at the other Party's sole expense, take commercially reasonable efforts to support and cooperate with the other Party in the conduct of its operations and the exercise of its rights hereunder, and in carrying out and otherwise giving full force and effect to the purpose and intent of this Agreement, including a Party's efforts to obtain from any governmental authority or any other Person any permit, entitlement, approval, authorization or other rights necessary or convenient in connection with its operations and/or the exercise of its rights hereunder; and each Party shall, without demanding additional consideration therefor, promptly execute, and, if appropriate, cause to be acknowledged and recorded, any map, application, document or instrument that is reasonably requested by the other Party or any governmental authority in connection therewith. 3.4 Certifications. Each Party shall, upon not less than ten (10) days' prior written notice from time to time given by the other Party or by any existing or proposed Lender, assignee or subgrantee (each, a "Requesting Party"), execute, acknowledge and deliver to the Requesting Party a written statement (a) certifying that this Agreement is unmodified and in full force and effect (or, if modified, stating the nature of such modification and certifying that this Agreement, as so modified, is in full force and effect), and (b) certifying that there are not, to the non-requesting Party's knowledge, any uncured defaults hereunder, or describing with particularity each such uncured default if any are claimed. Any such statements may be conclusively relied upon by the Requesting Party. The failure of the non-requesting Party to deliver any such statement within such time shall be conclusive upon such non-requesting Party that (i) this Agreement is in full force and effect and has not been modified and (ii) there are no uncured defaults hereunder. Further, the Parties shall, within ten (10) days after written notice from a Requesting Party, execute and deliver thereto a certificate to the effect that said Party (A) recognizes a particular entity as a Lender or assignee under this Agreement and (B) will accord to such entity all the rights and privileges of a Lender or assignee (as applicable) hereunder. 3.5 Miscellaneous. Except with respect to the rights of Lenders as set forth above, the covenants contained herein are made solely for the benefit of the Parties hereto, and shall not be construed as benefiting any Person that is not a Party to this Agreement. This Agreement shall be governed by, construed and enforced in accordance with the Laws of the State of New Mexico without regard to the conflicts of law principles of the State of New Mexico.
